SIMPLE: stiff
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stiff
<hw>Stiff</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos>
<adjf>Stiffer</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Stiffest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>stif</ets>, AS.
<ets>st⟦imac⟧f</ets>; akin to D. <ets>stijf</ets>, G. <ets>steif</ets>,
Dan. <ets>stiv</ets>, Sw. <ets>styf</ets>, Icel. <ets>st⟦imac⟧fr</ets>,
Lith. <ets>stipti</ets> to be stiff; cf. L. <ets>stipes</ets> a post,
trunk of a tree, <ets>stipare</ets> to press, compress. Cf.
<er>Costive</er>, <er>Stifle</er>, <er>Stipulate</er>, <er>Stive</er> to
stuff.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Not easily bent; not flexible or pliant;
not limber or flaccid; rigid; firm; <as>as, <ex>stiff</ex> wood, paper,
joints</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[They] rising on <qex>stiff</qex> pennons, tower⟦br⟧
The mid aerial sky.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Not liquid or fluid; thick and tenacious;
inspissated; neither soft nor hard; <as>as, the paste is
<ex>stiff</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Firm; strong; violent; difficult to oppose; <as>as,
a <ex>stiff</ex> gale or breeze</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Not easily subdued; unyielding; stubborn; obstinate;
pertinacious; <as>as, a <ex>stiff</ex> adversary</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is a shame to stand <qex>stiff</qex> in a foolish argument.</q>
<rj><qau>Jer. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A war ensues: the Cretans own their cause,⟦br⟧
<qex>Stiff</qex> to defend their hospitable laws.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Not natural and easy; formal; constrained; affected;
starched; <as>as, <ex>stiff</ex> behavior; a <ex>stiff</ex>
style</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The French are open, familiar, and talkative; the Italians
<qex>stiff</qex>, ceremonious, and reserved.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Harsh; disagreeable; severe; hard to bear.</def>
<mark>[Obs. or Colloq.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧This is <xex>stiff</xex>
news.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>Bearing a press of canvas without
careening much; <as>as, a <ex>stiff</ex> vessel</as>; -- opposed to
<contr>crank</contr>.</def> <rj><au>Totten.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>Very large, strong, or costly; powerful; <as>as, a
<ex>stiff</ex> charge; a <ex>stiff</ex> price</as>.</def>
<mark>[Slang]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Stiff neck</b></col>, <cd>a condition of the neck such
that the head can not be moved without difficulty and
pain.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Rigid; inflexible; strong; hardly; stubborn;
obstinate; pertinacious; harsh; formal; constrained; affected; starched;
rigorous.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stiff-backed</ent>⟦br⟧
